<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-224-332  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 224 332.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  March 30 1989 v15 n7 p29(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Growth of wide area networks slowed by regulation.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blackwell, Gerry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Demand for wide area networking products and services in Canada isgrowing, but the market is not growing as fast is it could due totight regulation of the nation's telecommunications industry.andO;Canadian demand for high-capacity transmission facilities isdriven by such factors as the proliferation of local areanetworks, increased automation by companies of their businessoperations, increased ease of automation, and the trend towardglobal automation.andP;  Use of T1 in Canada lags far behind that inthe US due primarily to pricing.andP;  In the US, deregulation hascreated a highly competitive market for digital networkingservices, and the free market environment has resulted inlower-priced bundled offerings.andP;  ISDN is expected to reduce thecost of access to telephone company-supplied data services.andO;Although it will not be widely available until the mid-1990s,users should start planning for it now.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CanadaMarketGovernment RegulationWide Area NetworksUnited StatesPriceEnd UsersISDN.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>